We are given a linked list data structure which will hold next [ value, next, random] : where next points to next element and random points to a random element in the list / null.
Our job is the arrive at the list that will have its next and random pointers pointing to the given input.


If this original node already has a copy, use that copy.
Do not create another duplicate node.


Idea:
We need to create a deep copy of a linked list where each node has two pointers:
1. next
2. random

The problem is that random can point to any node, even a node that was already copied or a node that appears later.

So we use a HashMap to store the mapping:

original node -> copied node

This helps us avoid creating duplicate copies of the same node.

Whenever we visit a node:
- If it is null, return null.
- If it is already copied, return the copied node from the map.
- Otherwise, create a new copy.
- Store original -> copy in the map.
- Recursively copy its next pointer.
- Recursively copy its random pointer.
- Return the copied node.


Code:

class Solution {

    HashMap<Node, Node> visitedNode = new HashMap<>();
    public Node copyRandomList(Node head) {

        if(head == null) return null;

        if(this.visitedNode.containsKey(head))
        {
            return this.visitedNode.get(head);
        }

        Node node = new Node(head.val, null, null);

        this.visitedNode.put(head, node);

        node.next = copyRandomList(head.next);
        node.random = copyRandomList(head.random);

        return node;
         
    }
}
